  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>A DCF is a snapshot based on estimates. Here are the primary risks to this valuation.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Faster Electrification:</strong> If EV adoption and industrial automation accelerate faster than anticipated, ADI's core markets could experience prolonged hyper-growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Synergy Realization:</strong> Further margin expansion from the integration of Maxim Integrated could drive FCF higher than our 9% growth estimate.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital Return:</strong> ADI consistently raises its dividend and buys back stock. Extensive buybacks would decrease share count, raising per-share intrinsic value over time.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Severe Cyclical Downturn:</strong> While analog chips are less volatile than memory or GPUs, a severe global recession would cause broad industrial and automotive order cancellations.</li>
    <li><strong>Automotive Market Weakness:</strong> The auto sector is a massive growth engine for ADI. Prolonged weakness or a price war in the EV market could pressure ADI's automotive revenues.</li>
    <li><strong>Geopolitical Tensions:</strong> The semiconductor supply chain is highly sensitive to US-China relations and trade restrictions.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a Two-Stage DCF for Analog Devices?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A two-stage model is ideal for a mature but growing company like ADI. It allows us to model a period of above-average growth (driven by secular tailwinds like EVs and 5G) before settling into a mature, long-term macroeconomic growth rate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the Terminal Growth Rate 3.5%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Analog chips have product lifecycles that can last over a decade. They are embedded in countless industrial, medical, and automotive devices. A 3.5% terminal rate assumes ADI will grow slightly faster than long-term inflation, reflecting the ongoing proliferation of electronics in the physical world.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does Debt impact this valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">ADI has significant debt ($8.59B) primarily stemming from its acquisition of Maxim Integrated. We must subtract Net Debt from Enterprise Value to find Equity Value. If ADI uses its massive free cash flow to rapidly pay down debt, the Equity Value will rise accordingly.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

